                                <h2>What is a TFSA?</h2>
                                <div class="decor-line"></div>
                            </div>
                            <p>A Tax-Free Savings Account (TFSA) is an account that grows tax free. You can hold a mix of investments and any investment income
                             earned in a TFSA (including interest, capital gains and dividends) is not taxed, even when withdrawn. That means it’s 100% yours to keep.</p><span class="space-25"></span><span class="border"></span><span class="space-15"></span>
                            <div>

                                <h4>What are the benefits of a TFSA?</h4>
                                <h6>Some of the benefits of a TFSA are:</h6>
                                <ul class="list-box">
                                    <li>-  Tax-free growth - you can save your money tax free for any goal you want (car, home, vacation)</li>
                                    <li>-  Tax-free withdrawals - you can take money out when you want for any reason</li>
                                    <li>-  Contribute up to $5,500 a year</li>
                                    <li>-  You can re-contribute any amounts you withdraw the following year in addition to the annual maximum</li>
                                    <li>-  You can put money into your spouse’s or common-law partner’s account</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                            <span class="space-25"></span><span class="border"></span><span class="space-15"></span>
                            <div>

                                <h4>Who is eligible for TFSA?</h4>
                                <h6>Most Canadians are eligible. To open a TFSA, you must:</h6>
                                <ul class="list-box">
                                    <li>-  have achieved the age of majority in your province or territory of residence (in Ontario, it is 18);</li>
                                    <li>-  be a Canadian resident; and</li>
                                    <li>-  have Canadian Social Insurance Number (SIN)</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                            <span class="space-25"></span><span class="border"></span><span class="space-15"></span>
